Street W1S 3NG London','Our distinguished gallery space at number 30 Cork Street was once home to the Peggy Guggenheim Gallery. Peggy Guggenheim was recognised as one of the most important names in the Art world through the Guggenheim Collection. The opening of the Guggenheim “Jeune” Gallery in January 1938 at 30 Cork Street, launched her career; a career that would decidedly alter the course of post-war Art. It was here where Wassily Kandinsky had his first ever London show.\nWe are in the heart of the Art district in Mayfair, minutes walk from the Royal Academy of Arts. Cork Street is known as the “Mecca” of Art galleries and is home to some of the most influential dealers of the world. Many major Art dealers have shown in Cork Street at some point or other. With Bond Street and the world’s most renowned auction houses – Sotheby’s and Christie’s just around the corner, it is the perfect breeding ground for Art talent, and Art trade.\nAt present, Cork Street is undergoing major redevelopments due for completion in 2017, which will see this street expand and welcome even more galleries and dealers.\nWe want to provide potential buyers with the most recent, comprehensive information on art, artists and their current and speculated position in the market. In order to achieve this, it is important to have a presence; a gallery, where works can be shown and living artists can be represented. This is done through Dadiani Fine Art dealership.\nAs well as numerous exhibitions, we host cultural events, talks and evenings dedicated to introduce and acquaint the  public to our artists and more.',NULL,0,51.5106077,'30 Cork Street W1S 3NG London',-0.141254600000025,'Dadiani Fine Art','Monday - Friday : 11:00 - 18:00, Saturday : 11:00 - 15:00',NULL,2,'dadianifineart.com',NULL),(105,'2016-07-01 15:44:39','2016-07-01 15:44:39','7a Wakefield Street WC1N 1PG London','Established in April 2013 and situated in Bloomsbury, Dairy Art Centre is a public space for contemporary visual art. It is a private, non commercial, organisation founded by Frank Cohen and Nicolai Frahm, cementing their lifelong passion for art and their commitment to increasing access to the visual arts by opening up Dairy’s exhibitions to the public for free, and through its newly created education and internship training programmes.',NULL,0,51.5259999,'7a Wakefield Street WC1N 1PG London',-0.122434800000065,'Dairy Art Centre','Tuesday - Friday : 10:00 - 18:00, Saturday - Sunday : 11:00 - 17:00',NULL,2,'dairyartcentre.org.uk',NULL),(106,'2016-07-01 15:44:40','2016-07-01 15:44:40','Daiwa Foundation, Japan House NW1 4QP London','The Daiwa Anglo-Japanese Foundation is a UK charity, established in 1988 with a generous benefaction from Daiwa Securities Co Ltd. The Foundation’s purpose is to support closer links between Britain and Japan.\n\nIt does this by:\n\n- making grants available to individuals, institutions and organisations to promote links between the UK and Japan across all fields of activity\n\n- awarding scholarships to young British graduates to study Japan and its language\n\n- organising a year-round programme of events to increase understanding of Japan in the UK\n\nDaiwa Foundation Japan House, the London-based headquarters, acts as a centre for UK-Japan relations in Britain by offering a wide programme of lectures, seminars, book launches, courses and exhibitions as well as meeting rooms for Japan-related activities and facilities for visiting academics.',NULL,0,51.5237176,'Daiwa Foundation, Japan House NW1 4QP London',-0.156563300000016,'Daiwa Anglo-Japanese Foundation','See the website for further details',NULL,2,'http://www.dajf.org.uk/events/current-exhibition',NULL),(107,'2016-07-01 15:44:43','2016-07-01 15:44:43','51 Hoxton Square N1 6PB London','Contemporary Art Gallery ',NULL,0,51.5271354,'51 Hoxton Square N1 6PB London',-0.0814596000000165,'Daniel Blau','Tuesday - Friday : 11:00 - 18:00',NULL,2,'www.danielblau.com',NULL),(108,'2016-07-01 15:44:43','2016-0