t-run and where programming would maintain a direct relationship to practice. Five Years continues to develop this aim of maintaining close links between the production and exhibition of work, and the discourse which informs it. Five Years consists of a membership of twelve contributors, each of whom may present two exhibition projects in the gallery every 18 months. Each contributor can choose to include their own work in one of these slots if they wish, but the other show must be purely invitational. Aside from these basic rules, each member acts autonomously of the others in deciding the nature and content of their contributions to Five Years’ exhibition programme. The creative freedom that this structure allows operates like an engine, generating a continuous, rapid succession of new projects and continuously branching out into unpredictable territory, beyond the control of any individual directorship.',NULL,0,51.5355002,'66 Regents Studios E8 4QN London',-0.0602433000000247,'Five Years','Saturday - Sunday : 13:00 - 18:00',NULL,2,'www.fiveyears.org.uk',NULL),(141,'2016-07-01 15:44:44','2016-07-01 15:44:44','210 Bellenden Road SE15 4BW London','Flat Time House (FTHo) was the studio home of John Latham (1921-2006), recognised as one of the most significant and influential British post-war artists. In 2003, Latham declared the house a living sculpture, naming it FTHo after his theory of time, ‘Flat Time’. Until his death, Latham opened his door to anyone interested in thinking about art. It is in this spirit that Flat Time House opened in 2008 as a gallery with a programme of exhibitions and events exploring the artist\'s practice, his theoretical ideas and their continued relevance. It also provides a centre for alternative learning, which includes the John Latham archive, and an artist\'s residency space. ',NULL,0,51.4668485,'210 Bellenden Road SE15 4BW London',-0.0732057000000168,'Flat Time House','Thursday - Sunday : 12:00 - 18:00',NULL,2,'www.flattimeho.org.uk',NULL),(142,'2016-07-01 15:44:55','2016-07-01 15:44:55','13 Berkeley Street W1J 8DU London','CLOSED',NULL,0,51.5082994,'13 Berkeley Street W1J 8DU London',-0.143135499999971,'Fleming Collection','Tuesday - Saturday : 10:00 - 17:30',NULL,2,'www.flemingcollection.com',NULL),(143,'2016-07-01 15:44:44','2016-07-01 15:44:44','21 Cork St W1S 3LZ London','Angela Flowers established her first gallery in 1970 on Lisle Street in London\'s West End. In the 1980s, the gallery was one of the first to open in London\'s East End, in a former laundry/fur storage facility in Hackney, and the space became known as Flowers East. Matthew Flowers, Angela\'s son, took over day to day operations in 1989. In 1997, the gallery expanded further with a Los Angeles space, at Bergamot Station.\n\nThere are now two gallery spaces in London: a West End premises on Cork Street opened in 2000 and in 2002 the gallery moved from Hackney into a 12,000 sq foot industrial space in Shoreditch, East London. The US business relocated in 2003 from LA to New York on Madison Avenue, and then in 2009 moved to West 20th street in Chelsea.\n\nFlowers participates regularly in art fairs internationally. The programme in both the UK and US comprises all media by established and emerging artists. The gallery is an active publisher of prints and multiples with an established department in contemporary international photography.',NULL,0,51.510137,'21 Cork St W1S 3LZ London',-0.141057600000067,'Flowers','Monday - Saturday : 10:00 - 18:00',NULL,2,'www.flowersgalleries.com',NULL),(144,'2016-07-01 15:44:44','2016-07-01 15:44:44','82 Kingsland Road E2 8DP London','Angela Flowers established her first gallery in 1970 on Lisle Street in London\'s West End. In the 1980s, the gallery was one of the first to open in London\'s East End, in a former laundry/fur storage facility in Hackney, and the space became known as Flowers East. Matthew Flowers, Angela\'s son, took over day to day operations in 1989. In 1997, the gallery expanded further with a Los Angeles space, at Bergamot Station.\n\nThere are now two gallery spaces in London: a West End premises on Cork Street opened in 2000 and in 2002 the gallery moved from Hackney into a 12,000 sq foot industrial space in Shoreditch, East London. The US business relocated in 2003 from LA to New York on Madison Avenue, and then in 2009 moved to West 20th street in Chelsea.\n\nFlowers participates regularly in art fairs internationally. The programme in both the UK and US comprises all media by established and emerging artists. The gallery is an active publisher of prints and multiples with an established department in contemporary international photography.',NULL,0,51.529646,'82 Kingsland Road E2 8DP London',-0.0771730000000162,'Flowers ','Tuesday - Saturday : 10:00 - 18:00',NULL,2,'www.flowersgalleries.com',NULL),(145,'2016-07-01 15:44:44','2016-07-01 15:44:44','158 New Cavendish Street W1W 6YW London','FOLD has been operating commercially since 2012 and has established a strong profile, with a reputation for accessible shows, that promote new art and challenge artistic conventions.\nThe gallery has a programme of curated group shows, which give an opportunity for UK based and international artists, from emerging to mid-career practices, to be brought together within context. In conjunction with significant solo exhibitions, FOLD presents the viewer with the best opportunity to gain an understanding of the intentions of the artist, whilst viewing the work displayed to the highest standards within the lexicon of contemporary art.',NULL,0,51.5205341,'158 New Cavendish Street W1W 6YW London',-0.139466699999957,'FOLD','Wednesday - Saturday : 12:00 - 18:00 or by appointment',NULL,2,'www.foldgallery.com',NULL),(146,'2016-07-01 15:44:44','2016-07-01 15:44:44','20 Clerkenwell Green EC1R 0DP London','Our mission is to promote and support the very best emerging and established contemporary artists with cutting-edge projects and exhibitions.  Working at the grass roots of art-making enables us to source exceptional artworks for private clients and institutions alike. At Frameless Gallery utmost importance is given to the process of discovering, exhibiting and building long-lasting relationships with artists and collectors that strive for excellence, craftsmanship and beauty. ',NULL,0,51.5227692,'20 Clerkenwell Green EC1R 0DP London',-0.104952400000002,'Frameless Gallery','By appointment only',NULL,2,'www.framelessgallery.com',NULL),(147,'2016-07-01 15:44:44','2016-07-01 15:44:44','58 Gloucester Road SW7 4QT London','Since 2006 >french art studio promotes the French art scene in the UK and around the world. We are the leading French contemporary art gallery in London, with a reputed exhibition space located 58 Gloucester Road in Kensington. Our intimate knowledge of the French art world helps us spotting and showcasing talent you can\'t find elsewhere. In a friendly atmosphere, we have curated a rich selection of paintings, sculptures and photographs that often surprise and seduce art amateurs looking for something with distinct personality.',NULL,0,51.4980861,'58 Gloucester Road SW7 4QT London',-0.184049200000004,'French Art Studio','Monday - Saturday : 9:30 - 18:30 or by appointment',NULL,2,'www.frenchartstudio.com',NULL),(148,'2016-07-01 15:44:44','2016-07-01 15:44:44','309 Bethnal Green Road E2 6AH London','French Riviera is a gallery in Bethnal Green, East London, presented by artists Samuel Levack and Jennifer Lewandowski as an extension of their long-standing collaboration. Occupying their studio in a former shop on Bethnal Green Road, the gallery offers a platform to artists who are currently without representation in the UK.',NULL,0,51.5265627,'309 Bethnal Green Road E2 6AH London',-0.0652076000000079,'French Riviera','Friday - Sunday : 12:00 - 18:00, or by appointment',NULL,2,'www.frenchriviera1988.com',NULL),(149,'2016-07-01 15:44:54','2016-07-01 15:44:54','20 Maresfield gardens NW3 5SX London','The Freud Museum, at 20 Maresfield Gardens in Hampstead, was the home of Sigmund Freud and his family when they escaped Austria following the Nazi annexation in 1938. It remained the family home until Anna Freud, the youngest daughter, died in 1982. The centrepiece of the museum is Freud\'s study, preserved just as it was during his lifetime.\n\nIt contains Freud\'s remarkable collection of antiquities: Egyptian; Greek; Roman and Oriental. Almost 2,000 items fill cabinets and are arranged on every surface. There are rows of ancient figures on the desk where Freud wrote until the early hours of the morning. The walls are lined with shelves containing Freud\'s large library.\n\nThe house is also filled with memories of his daughter, Anna, who lived there for 44 years and continued to develop her pioneering psychoanalytic work, especially with children. It was her wish that the house become a museum to honour her illustrious father. The Freuds were fortunate to be able to bring all their furniture and household effects to London. These included splendid Biedermeier chests, tables and cupboards, and a fine collection of 18th and 19th century Austrian painted country furniture. The Museum engages actively with Sigmund and Anna\'s psychoanalytic legacy in contemporary ideas, art, and culture, while caring for the house and collections.',NULL,0,51.548836,'20 Maresfield gardens NW3 5SX London',-0.177442599999949,'Freud Museum','Wednesday - Sunday : 12:00 - 17:00',NULL,2,'www.freud.org.uk',NULL),(150,'2016-07-01 15:44:40','2016-07-01 15:44:40','South of The Regent\'s Park NW1 4NR London','Frieze London features more than 160 of the world’s leading galleries. View and buy art from over 1,000 of today’s leading artists, and experience the fair’s critically acclaimed Frieze Projects and Talks programmes.',NULL,0,51.52832,'South of The Regent\'s Park NW1 4NR London',-0.150740400000018,'Frieze London','See the website for further details',NULL,2,'friezelondon.com',NULL),(151,'2016-07-01 15