n, Anya Gallaccio, Gary Hume, Michael Landy, Bob Law, Gerhard Richter, Bridget Riley, Ed Ruscha, John Stezaker, Rachel Whiteread, Alison Wilding and Fred Wilson.\n \nAlongside the gallery, Karsten Schubert (with Charles Asprey and Thomas Dane) established the publishing company Ridinghouse in 1995. This London-based press is dedicated to publishing the best of art writing and criticism, revisiting art history and exploring individual artists and specific projects through its expanding lists. \n \nKarsten Schubert continues to nurture its represented artists – Robert Holyhead, Ann-Marie James, Bridget Riley and Alison Wilding – at its current space on Lexington Street, Soho, through co-organising exhibitions with galleries at home and abroad. The company also oversees an off-site events programme and participates at numerous national and international art and book fairs.\n \nKarsten Schubert, the company\'s founder, was born in Berlin, Germany in 1961. He is an Advisory Board member of Drawing Room, London, and a Faculty of the Fine Arts member of The British School at Rome. ',NULL,0,51.5131352,'46 Lexington Street W1F 0LP London',-0.136193999999932,'Karsten Schubert','Monday - Friday : 10:00 - 18:00, viewing by appointment only',NULL,2,'www.karstenschubert.com',NULL),(215,'2016-07-01 15:44:45','2016-07-01 15:44:45','27 Old Nichol Street E2 7HR London','',NULL,0,51.5247932,'27 Old Nichol Street E2 7HR London',-0.0740763000000016,'Kate MacGarry','Wednesday - Saturday : 12:00 - 18:00, or by appointment',NULL,2,'www.katemacgarry.com',NULL),(216,'2016-07-01 15:44:39','2016-07-01 15:44:39','110-116 Kingsgate Road NW6 2JG London','Kingsgate Workshops is a multi-use art space housed within a labyrinthine Victorian factory, providing affordable workspace for an exciting mix of artists, makers and designers. \n \nKingsgate Workshops’ Public Programme encourages experimentation, production and critical discourse.  We support a crossover between disciplines, an exchange of skills and the development of critical and timely conversations about process, image making and object making. Our Project Space aims to profile a diverse range of contemporary national and international artists with a focus on emerging talent.',NULL,0,51.5439888,'110-116 Kingsgate Road NW6 2JG London',-0.196629600000051,'Kingsgate Workshops','By appointment only',NULL,2,'www.kingsgateworkshops.org.uk',NULL),(217,'2016-07-01 15:44:45','2016-07-01 15:44:45','54 Atlantic Road  SW9 8PZ London','Knight Webb Gallery was opened in November 2012 by abstract painter Rufus Knight-Webb, and is a contemporary art space in Brixton, London. The exhibition program focuses on a group of emerging and established artists from London, the USA, Africa and Germany, with the aim of developing careers and bringing obscured art practices onto the open playing field. The gallery participates in numerous overseas and UK artfairs, and has established a reputation for supporting individualism and psychology in artistic practice.',NULL,0,51.4615862,'54 Atlantic Road  SW9 8PZ London',-0.111792299999934,'Knight Webb Gallery','Tuesday - Saturday : 10:00 - 18:00, or by appointment',NULL,2,'www.knightwebbgallery.com',NULL),(218,'2016-07-01 15:44:45','2016-07-01 15:44:45','533 Old York Road SW18 1TG London','Established in 2012, Kristin Hjellegjerde Gallery is quickly gaining recognition for showing a roster of innovative, international artists, both emerging and established, with strong theoretical and aesthetic bases.\n \nNamed one of Blouin\'s 500 Best Galleries Worldwide in 2015 and The Londonist\'s Independent Gallery of the Year in 2014, the gallery showcases cutting-edge contemporary art with the central concern being the creation of a focused, intimate space in which artists can present a coherent body of work. Drawing on her own international background, Hjellegjerde seeks to discover and develop new talents by creating a platform through which she introduces them to local and international audiences and allows for artistic exchange.\n \nThe gallery is expanding into the realm of international art fairs, and in 2016 opened Kristin Hjellegjerde Projects, a second space featuring small, curated solo shows by emerging artists. Hjellegjerde also acts as an art advisor for private and corporate collectors, as well as working closely with developers and architects.',NULL,0,51.4598247,'533 Old York Road SW18 1TG London',-0.188807200000042,'Kristin Hjellegjerde','Tuesday - Saturday : 11:00 - 18:00',NULL,2,'www.kristinhjellegjerde.com',NULL),(219,'2016-07-01 15:44:46','2016-07-01 15:44:46','15a Cremer Street E2 8HD London','Contemporary Art Gallery ',NULL,0,51.5305378,'15a Cremer Street E2 8HD London',-0.0761694999999918,'Kunstraum','Thursday - Saturday : 12:00 - 18:00',NULL,2,'kunstraum.org.uk',NULL),(220,'2016-07-01 15:44:46','2016-07-01 15:44:46','44a Charlotte Road EC2A 3PD London','Contemporary Art Gallery ',NULL,0,51.5254814,'44a Charlotte Road EC2A 3PD London',-0.0809524999999667,'l\'̩etrang̬ere','Tuesday - Saturday : 11:00 - 18:00, or by appointment',NULL,2,'letrangere.net',NULL),(221,'2016-07-01 15:44:46','2016-07-01 15:44:46','5b Pall Mall SW1Y 4UY London','The most prestigious Contemporary Art Gallery and Auction House for hire in London.\nLocated within 5 minutes walk from Sotheby\'s, Christie\'s,The National Gallery and The West End Theatres,\nwe are ideally located to place art in front of both National and International buyers.\nThe Galleria host numerous prestigious International Art Exhibitions every year as well as regular corporate\nlaunch events and cocktails.',NULL,0,51.5078383,'5b Pall Mall SW1Y 4UY London',-0.132216800000037,'La Galleria Pall Mall','See the website for further details',NULL,2,'www.lagalleria.org',NULL),(222,'2016-07-01 15:44:46','2016-07-01 15:44:46','8 Clarendon Cross W11 4AP London','LACEY CONTEMPORARY GALLERY launched during the autumn of 2014 in Clarendon Cross W11. Founded by Andrew Lacey, Lacey Contemporary represents UK-based contemporary artists, and supports artists from emerging contemporary markets.\n\nThe selected artists are recognised for their excellence in craftsmanship and technique whilst also demonstrating unique experimentation in their processes and concepts. The artists represent the diverse styles of British contemporary art, from both emerging talents such as Katrine Roberts who is currently finishing her MA at the Royal College of Arts, to more seasoned artists such as Laurence Wood, who has been exhibiting for over 20 years, with collections in the Royal Residences and the National Trust Foundation for Art.',NULL,0,51.5104931,'8 Clarendon Cross W11 4AP London',-0.210201999999981,'Lacey Contemporary Gallery','Tuesday - Friday : 10:00 - 18:00, Saturday : 11:00 - 17:00, Sunday and Monday by appointment',NULL,2,'www.laceycontemporarygallery.co.uk',NULL),(223,'2016-07-01 15:44:46','2016-07-01 15:44:46','10 White Horse Street  W1J 7LJ London','LAMB Arts was established to promote the exchange between artistic and curatorial practices, markets and institutional projects between Latin America and Europe.\n\nWith a permanent space in Mayfair, LAMB Arts opens a cultural program between London, São Paulo and Latin America.',NULL,0,51.5062504,'10 White Horse Street  W1J 7LJ London',-0.146057499999984,'LAMB Arts','Tuesday - Friday : 11:00 - 18:00, Saturday : 12:00 - 17:00 ',NULL,2,'http://www.lamb-arts.com',NULL),(224,'2016-07-01 15:44:46','2016-07-01 15:44:46','392 Caledonian Road N1 1DN London','Something of a gallery and a shop (it could be called a gallop)...\n\nLarge Glass was founded in 2011 by Charlotte Schepke, as a commercial space for new encounters. Guided by the spirit of Marcel Duchamp, it aims to show contemporary art through a particular and uncommon lens, presenting individually conceived and curated exhibitions on a diversity of themes.\n\nIt is sited on the Caledonian Road, between Kings Cross and Islington, off the traditional gallery circuit. Large Glass is a place to contemplate and discuss art, as well as buy it; where works of international artists are sold alongside objects and editions; where there are probing discussions, as well as wine tastings; where artists come to make and show art, and also to cook. ',NULL,0,51.5426226,'392 Caledonian Road N1 1DN London',-0.117106899999953,'Large Glass Gallery','Wednesday - Saturday : 11:00 - 18:00, or by appointment',NULL,2,'http://largeglass.co.uk',NULL),(225,'2016-07-01 15:44:46','2016-07-01 15:44:46','4 Herald Street E2 6JT London','Contemporary Art Gallery ',NULL,0,51.5251689,'4 Herald Street E2 6JT London',-0.0559683999999834,'Laura Bartlett Gallery','Wednesday – Saturday : 11:00 – 18:00, Sunday : 12:00 – 18:00',NULL,2,'www.laurabartlettgallery.com',NULL),(226,'2016-07-01 15:44:46','2016-07-01 15:44:46','42 New Compton Street WC2H 8DA London','Lawrence Alkin Gallery is an independently run, commercial art gallery located in the centre of London. Operating from our split-level boutique space that was once TomTom and, until recently, artrepublic Soho, the primary goal for us is to seek to develop the next generation of artists through exciting and different exhibitions, events and exclusive publications from a breadth of talent. Contemporary, urban, street and pop art; we don’t distinguish or discriminate, but embrace and look to display visually engaging exhibitions from a hybrid of artistic disciplines.\n\nThe gallery’s core principal of offering affordable original artworks and limited editions is combined with the belief that the work on display must have a strong visual impact and high quality production. This is what unites all of the artists we work with as many experiment with a variety of different media from a multitude of backgrounds and disciplines.',NULL,0,51.515427,'42 New Compton Street WC2H 8DA London',-0.127640199999973,'Lawrence Alkin Gallery','Monday - Saturday : 11:00 - 19:00, or by appointment',NULL,2,'www.lawrencealkingallery.com',NULL),(227,'2016-07-01 15:44:46','2016-07-01 15:44:46','11 Rathbone Place W1T 1HR London','Set in the heart of London\'s Fitzrovia, Lazarides Rathbone exhibits many of the most significant artists thriving outside the conventional contemporary art market. While Lazarides is considered the international market leader in what is dubbed urban art, many of the contemporary artists on display defy categorisation. Since being founded in 2006 Lazarides has been a constant force in championing the careers of artists who have transformed the way art is made and presented. These include a generation of pioneering street artists such as Mode 2, Invader and Todd James alongside influential British portrait artists Jonathan Yeo and Antony Micallef.\n\nSince its inception Lazarides Rathbone has hosted a variety of prolific exhibitions spanning both the ground and first floor levels, including JR\'s global Inside Out initiative and 3D\'s major retrospective of Massive Attack visual history. The gallery is involved in extensive off-site activity, incorporating one-off shows in New York and Los Angeles as well as art fairs and museum collaborations across London and Europe.',NULL,0,51.5169912,'11 Rathbone Place W1T 1HR London',-0.133254800000032,'Lazarides','Wednesday - Saturday : 11:00 - 19:00, Tuesday : by appointment',NULL,2,'www.lazinc.com',NULL),(228,'2016-07-01 15:44:39','2016-07-01 15:44:39','140 Lewisham Way SE14 6PD London','Lewisham Arthouse supports artists and arts-based learning through creative workspace and specialist facilities. We run an exhibition and events programmes of visual art and experimental music.\n\nMembers of Lewisham Art House share their time, equipment and knowledge with wider communities on a non-profit basis. Besides renting space, each studio member commits at least 5 hours per month in support of the organisation’s wider programmes. Each year, this generates in-kind support work more than £27,000.\n\nThis echoes the original intentions of the Carnegie library