lished in 1980 the Railings Gallery has become one of London’s leading contemporary art galleries and picture framers, specialising in original limited edition prints by artists from all over the world.',NULL,0,51.5188313,'5 New Cavendish Street W1G 8UT London',-0.1512113,'Railings Gallery','Monday-Thursday : 9:30-18:00,  Friday : 9:30-17:30,  Saturday : 10:00-17:30',NULL,2,'www.railings-gallery.com',NULL),(312,'2016-07-01 15:44:48','2016-07-01 15:44:48','105 Pimlico road SW1W 8LS London','Founded by Mark Ransom in 1990 and situated on the Pimlico Road in the heart of Chelsea, Ransom is one of London’s leading dealers in contemporary art, photography and design.\n\nWe offer rare and unique photographs and works of art from established names such as Francis Bacon, Salvador Dali, Lucian Freud, Andy Warhol, William Scott and Banksy; to the more recently acclaimed Tim Woolcock, Masaki Yada, Enrico Robusti, Marco Grassi/Grama, Pier Toffoletti, Gianfranco Meggiato and Walter Trecchi.\n\nWe have a wide selection of Terry O’Neill’s iconic photography. Terry is one of the world\'s most collected photographers with photos exhibiting in art galleries and prestigious private collections. \n\nWe have a number of exhibitions throughout the year and keep a constantly changing collection of works on display to be perused.  In addition we have an eclectic selection of design pieces for both interior designers and private clients.\n\nThe gallery has a reputation for excellence, integrity and discretion that it continues to earn by providing an excellent service to discerning clients.',NULL,0,51.4902829,'105 Pimlico road SW1W 8LS London',-0.15481520000003,'Ransom','Monday - Saturday : 10:00 - 18:00',NULL,2,'www.markransom.co.uk',NULL),(313,'2016-07-01 15:44:48','2016-07-01 15:44:48','185 Queens Crescent NW5 4DS London','From mid 2013 Martina Geccelli has set up this art and architecture project space within her own studio in Kentish Town, London.\n\nPart of the concept is that selected artists, or architects can introduce their work to a smaller, interested audience . RAUMX provides an open, intimate platform,  outside of the commercial setting of a gallery. Beside presenting work to the public the space offers opportunities for an active exchange in form of talks and discussions and more intimate gatherings.',NULL,0,51.550739,'185 Queens Crescent NW5 4DS London',-0.150220900000022,'RAUMX','See the website for further details',NULL,2,'www.raumx-london.com',NULL),(314,'2016-07-01 15:44:48','2016-07-01 15:44:48','56 Artillery Lane E1 7LS London','Raven Row is a non-profit contemporary art exhibition centre in Spitalfields that is open free to the public, Wednesdays to Sundays. It has been constructed within eighteenth century domestic rooms, onto which 6a architects have added two contemporary galleries, and it stands on the part of Artillery Lane that was known as Raven Row until 1895.\n \nRaven Row’s programme is intended to appeal both to a specialist audience and a broader, curious public. It is led by a desire to test art\'s purpose outside the market place. It will exhibit diverse work of the highest quality, often by established international artists, or those from the recent past, who have somehow escaped London\'s attention. However, the programme will remain improvisatory and un-dogmatic, and the qualities that might constitute Raven Row’s success, its ‘cultural value’, will remain open to question. \n\n\nFlats in the building’s upper floors host visiting artists and curators, invited to contribute to the exhibition programme. Four Corners Books, an acclaimed non-profit publisher of artists’ books and books on art are based in the building and will occasionally programme exhibitions and share events.',NULL,0,51.5183431,'56 Artillery Lane E1 7LS London',-0.0783122000000276,'Raven Row','Wednesday - Sunday : 11:00 - 19:00',NULL,2,'www.ravenrow.org',NULL),(315,'2016-07-01 15:44:48','2016-07-01 15:44:48','14 Greek Street W1D 4DP London','Loca